reasoning: 1. Circle of Competence: I’ve spent my life in businesses I understand—Coke, insurance, railroads. Alphabet’s core is search algorithms and digital advertising, wrapped in ever–shifting technology. That’s outside my circle, so I can’t have a high conviction here.  2. Moat: Google has a formidable network effect—billions of users feeding data into its engine and advertisers following the eyeballs. That’s a true competitive advantage, but it’s built on technology that evolves fast.  3. Management: Sundar Pichai and team have allocated capital wisely—strong returns, modest buybacks, sensible reinvestment in AI. They play it straight, which I respect, but they face regulators and competitors at every turn.  4. Financial Health: Alphabet sits on a fortress balance sheet, with ample cash, no serious debt, and consistently robust free cash flow. That part looks a lot like the companies I favor.  5. Valuation: With no reliable intrinsic‐value estimate provided, I can’t judge margin of safety. In past tech bubbles, I’ve seen share prices get well ahead of value.  6. Long-Term Prospects: I’m comfortable that Google will be around in 20 years, but rapid technology change introduces execution risk.  7. Comparison: I’d rather own an enduring consumer franchise—like Coke, which I’ve held for over 30 years—at a fair price than a complex tech leader at an unknown valuation.  So, neutral. I don’t love it enough to leap in, nor do I see red flags so big I’d short it. I’ll pass if the price isn’t compelling and wait for something in my wheelhouse.
